The architects saw - the office also includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini kindergarten here, with everything that includes: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to Arch.Design employees since last year.
The design and architecture firm Arch.Design, from whose studios a number of well-known Brünner buildings come, calculated from the first designs for the new building Avriopoint with the premises for its company mini-kindergarten.
In a wise perspective, because most of his 90 employees are in the baby boom age and the company is in the position to return to their workplace as soon as possible.
Together with the possibility to work shortened, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the concept of their social program.
The civil engineers have made it easier to bring their demanding profession and childcare under one roof.
The Mini Kindergarten is an original idea of Arch.Design’s employees and with the support of the management, they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The operational mini-kindergarten is financed by the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment Policy from the resources of the European Social Fund and from the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to this financing (CZK 2.8 million grants), the necessary facilities and equipment could be procured and for the duration of 2 years qualified personnel and for operation is provided.
After the funding has been exhausted (2 years), Arch.Design is obliged to continue operating the Minikindergarten 3 more years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took a whole year, with the Society providing active assistance in the processing of applications.
All-day qualified staff take care of the children - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can visit children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is a mini-kindergarten, only 5 children may be present at the same time, but the day will alternate over several children.
The kindergarten company is flexibly adapted to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights in relation to the use of the kindergarten - without regard to the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is individual education and care, the program content in the mini-kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the supporting program of pre-school education.
The children play here not only, but above all they are offered excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to pre-school lessons, in addition they also learn English.
The classroom is equipped not only with toys and creative games, but also with a computer that is available to the children.
What's more - the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive corporate environment.
The parents can take a look at the children at any time and thus the stress of late collection of the children from a far away kindergarten is eliminated.
Parents use their working hours more productively.
No wonder that there are also natural and loyal employer-employee relationships.
Arch.Design thus ranked among the Czech companies, which offer significant benefits in recruiting new employees, who are family-friendly and through such programs strengthen their staff marketing.
A bone house fascinates even after 100 years. Check out Gaudi’s interiors
The roof resembles the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are torn fish m<0xC3><0xA4>uler.
This is the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> of the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
Of the local inhabitants, the house with its organic forms was nicknamed "Knochenhaus".
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile splinters and mosaics, the dandruff-remembering facades and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of Antonio Gaudi’s Art Nouveau style.
The fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade of the house plays with dreamy lines, tender colors and textures reminiscent of nature and living beings.
It is only with a closer look that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thought-out order.
At night, the whole facade looks even more plastic, more dramatic and the special lighting enhances the luster of the colours.
The same swinging lines and intricate shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even look holes and strips.
The house Batll<0xC3><0xB3> in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Gr<0xC3><0xA1>cia No. 43 was built by the reconstruction of a house from 1877, which architect Emilio Sala Cortese carried out.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, originally consisted of the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but ultimately he agreed to the idea of Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>s for an unusual and also cheaper conversion.
The Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> rental house, however, did not design Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was precisely on his drawing board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the reality owner were created and also the use of mosaics on the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade was his idea.
However, numerous other sculptors and artists also worked on the design of the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade.
The joint work on the designs for the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s Casa Mil<0xC3><0xA1> in the Güell Park, where there are also other works by Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Shortly after its completion, the house was given by the local inhabitants of its organic forms because of the nickname "Knochenhaus".
Others, in turn, called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "coming house".
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of Saint George, patron of Catalonia.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> designed a central heating system with ventilation ducts and typical fireplaces that were unique to the house at the time.
A bit bizarre, their 45-degree inclination is already hinting at.
In his work, Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> consistently ignored all the building regulations at the time and was by no means fooled by them.
Before the start of construction, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he gave about the planned reconstruction was so vague that the city fathers were so horrified at the completion two years later that they demanded relief.
Among other things, the councilors also encountered the fact that the construction with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
However, there were no further changes, quite the contrary - only fifteen days after the district's request in this respect, Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3> submitted a request for permission to lease the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor there was a social lounge, on the third floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building goes through a staircase all the way up to the roof terrace.
Due to the basic elements of the conversion, all right angles and straight lines were removed and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> also worked with a modern concept for the mutual connection of spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and so a larger society could easily chat without having to forgo a certain intimacy in more confidential conversations.
The house received a rather unusual roof and two other floors through Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>'s conversion in addition to a new fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s play with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is dressed and the lighthouses.
The play of these two colors gives a maximum of light to all floors of the house.
He simply made use of the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colors that absorb the sunlight on the contrary.
The Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> house, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can be visited by anyone today.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is made accessible to the public.
The homeowners only decided in the year to take this step and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was found that this was a fairly profitable business, the visits were kept, yes it was extended to other common areas and the attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price for visiting the monument is not a cardboard stall, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards get 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, you should try to make friendships with one of the house dwellers and visit him at home.
The right mattress and the right bed rest? Women have different wishes than men
Not the best bed frame, but the quality of the lying area - so mattress and rust make up the good bed.
However, these must complement each other harmoniously in order to meet the wishes of the specific user.
When choosing, many things play a role - the weight, the size, the state of health and, last but not least, the sex of the sleeper.
Equally important is the interior in which mattress and rust have to be subordinated.
Typical example?
In a weekend house where not regularly heated, latex mattresses are not well suited, as they take much longer to "get warm".
In addition, they are significantly heavier than conventional polyurethane mattresses.
And - they should be turned regularly.
If they do not have enough venting channels in the core and are also on a solid plate, moisture accumulates: it is therefore not excluded that it forms under their mold.
Of course, the choice also plays a role in what you are used to.
If you have been abroad for a long time, where very high soft-layer mattresses are common, it will be difficult to get used to a low hard-surface mattress.
"Whether all hockey players who have come back from the NHL have complained to me that they can't sleep right here anymore."
"For their shrunken shoulders, heels and hips, they just need a soft layer of visco foam (memory foam - a shape memory polymer)."
"I also recommend these to people with diabetes who suffer from nervous system disorders, so that they can receive the "information" from the joints and skin badly," explains Sylva Hadamczikov<0xC3><0xA1>, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
That’s why I bought these mattresses with Visco foam (Memory Foam) from many ice hockey players years ago, but also from other customers.
"Today, this is no longer a problem, because such mattresses offer, among others, the manufacturer Tempur, the Italian company Magniflex or the Czech manufacturer Tropico."
And you don’t necessarily have to be a famous ice hockey player to appreciate the benefits of Visco foam.
This "miracle" actually works quite simply.
The foam optimizes its hardness and shape according to the absorbed heat, in other words, it really conforms to the warm body.
Nowhere does it press, at night you do not roll around like after a heavy battle.
You just sleep much better.
The viscoelastic foam also offers protection against decubitus (wound burn).
When choosing the mattress size, the length of the soles of the feet should still be added to the height, i.e. about 21 to 34 cm.
Man and woman, who are 180 cm tall, need a 210 to 220 cm bed.
Each sleeper should have at least 90 cm lying width available, i.e. 180 cm together.
For single beds, for example for singles, 120 to 140 cm are attached.
For the sake of comfort and also for any visitors.
Otherwise, the following rule of thumb applies to the ideal bed width: "If you are lying on your back, there should still be enough room for the slightly angled arms", advises Ing. Helena Prokopov<0xC3><0xA1>, the assistant master of upholsterers and room equipment, who has been dedicated to the problem of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture for years and this topic is also dedicated to specialist schools.
With a double bed, everyone needs their own grate and mattress, but be careful when shopping so that the mattresses are the same height.
Otherwise, there is nothing left but to mount the grate at different heights and this is not possible with every bed frame.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, mattresses with a spring skeleton 15 cm, of which at least three centimetres should be applied to the mould layer and the fine padding.
"By hand or while sitting down, you can't feel the feathers in any way," warns Helena Prokopov<0xC3><0xA1>.
Each mattress requires a special type of rust.
Fully upholstered beds with mattress and underlay like grown Siam twins have nothing to look for in the bedroom.
These mattresses cannot be ventilated and the cover can not be washed, which is already happening today.
And since you lose between 0.2 and 0.75 l of sweat in a single night, it is clear that after five to seven years, the mattress slowly becomes a huge (and clogged sieve).
This is also why professionals reject advertising slogans that promise a lifetime of up to 25 years, even life-long warranty, for mattresses.
Every thing has its if and but.
And therefore a practical advice from the dealers: For mattresses of 120 or 140 cm width one should not shy away from the hygiene of the washable, removable covers, but it is recommended to use a mattress protector that can be easily removed and washed.
Even though mattress covers with a full zip are usually made today, so that after opening you get two halves (immensally important for the washing process and the washing machine size!), the manipulation with larger mattresses, especially executed alone, often resembles the unequal struggle between David and Goliath.
Do they have a solid plate in bed instead of a grate?
Get out of here!
Or at most for a bed for unloved guests and for a single night.
Even so, they should rather provide the plate with ventilation holes (unless they are already in it) and use mattresses with spring skeleton and 15 cm minimum height with so-called pocket spring cores and fine cushions.
Polyurethane mattresses do not belong on such a substrate.
For non-adjustable slatted gratings with 14 to 18 spring strips (lamellas) latex or sandwich mattresses (if applicable also combinations of latex and coconut) always pay for slatted gratings with a larger number of slatted bars, i.e. of 28 and more spring strips, with lordose support in the lumbar region and the possibility of regulating the slat hardness.
Adjustable slatted gratings do not include mattresses with a spring skeleton, as they do not respond to the ergonomic adjustment.
In addition to adjusting the stiffness of the spring strips, special flexible shoulder modules are also offered.
This involves a special fastening of the spring strips, which makes it possible to press the spring strips or even to angle them in such a way that they make it possible for the shoulder of the sleeper to sink in to a point.
Especially for men with broad shoulders an important thing.
There are even mattress manufacturers who have started using soft zones for the shoulder area in "men's mattresses".
The ladies are also thought of - they are given these soft zones in the hip area.
For the most demanding customers, point-elastic wing spring systems (Lattoflex) or rust with point-elastic contact pads with so-called multitorsion springing are designed.
The pressure is distributed over several points, reducing the voltage.
But - if you use a bad (too big and full) pillow for the right mattress and rust, most benefits are lost again.
Here, too, a rule of thumb: the pillow should support the head, its tips should only reach up to the shoulders so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
Therefore, a 50 x 60 cm cushion appears ideal, as the Scandinavians, for example, like.
In the side position, the pillow (together with the shoulder relief zone in the grate or the soft zone in the mattress) should balance the shoulder height.
Our modern mattresses have something in common with the former (filled with hay) straw sacks.
Modern manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials or at least their admixtures.
The word “bio” is also used in mattresses.
Instead of petroleum raw materials, natural oils are increasingly used for the production of polyurethane foams - for example castor and soybean oil.
Soy is probably used by all well-known manufacturers.
“Bio means for mattresses that are made of materials of purely natural origin,” explains Petr Va<0xC5><0xA1><0xC3><0xAD><0xC4><0x8D>ek from Tropico Plus.
However, natural materials are also used in the production of mattress covers - one of the first was aloe vera.
However, you can also enjoy microcapsules that spread fresh forest or lavender scent when you sleep.
Here, too, there is a difference between man and woman.
While men use a "cooling" plant extract of birch leaves to allow the mattress cover to absorb heat and cool the body, the covers have "warming" effect for women.
Extracts from red peppers stimulate blood circulation, so the weaker sex gets warm when you sleep.
And today's favorites?
Mattresses made of cold foam (it has larger pores with destroyed cell structure and is therefore more breathable than commercially available polyurethane and also much more flexible).
The combination of the different stiffness (hardness) of cold foams and visco foams creates multi-zone mattresses that know exactly where the head, hip and heel are located.
