The Democratic Routine
The democratic movement in Latin America is becoming stronger, as is the support of private companies.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, Brazil’s influence is greater than that of the United States.
These results were obtained by the Latinobar<0xC3><0xB3>metro survey, which was conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been conducted on a regular basis since 1995 and thus shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts are particularly important in this year’s September and October survey.
First, the good mood in Latin America
And secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its main institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has increased sharply (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has grown by about 6% annually since 2002, the number of democracy advocates rose from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Even in Mexico, where the economy has recovered since the sharp collapse of last year, such a trend can be seen.
However, only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the region’s most populous countries, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see diagram 2).
About 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with the democratic practice of their country, which is as many as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (chart 3).
About 34% trust the Congress of their country and 45% of their government. Both values correspond to those of last year, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America’s economic crises undermined efforts to achieve more democracy.
This continued even during the global economic crisis, perhaps because the countries of Latin America experienced only a brief recession and recovered quickly.
In addition, the poor were caught up by a stronger social network.
(According to reports by the United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America this week, in 2009 the poverty rate in Latin America rose only slightly and fell by 32% again this year.)
But there are strong mood differences from country to country (see diagram 4).
Brazil’s strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz In<0xC3><0xA1>cio Lula da Silva is reflected in a widespread thinking of progress.
In Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more noticeable and violent crimes have increased, this is less so.
For the second time since the start of the survey, many respondents in Latin America see a greater problem in crime in their country than in unemployment (see diagram 5).
About 31% say that either they themselves or a family member were the victims of a crime last year, but compared to 38% last year, values have fallen, reaching the lowest level since 1995.
The increase in economic performance is reflected in the increased support of the private sector and the market economy: approximately 71% of respondents nationwide stated that the private sector is indispensable for development, in 2007 it was 56% (see diagram 6).
About 58% said that only the market economy can bring their country progress, compared to 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela have maintained this view (and 80% are for a private economy), although their left-wing president, Hugo Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez, nationalized many private companies.
Brazil has the largest weight in the region, according to 19% of respondents (18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged since last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% last year).
Respondents in Mexico and most of Central America, on the other hand, see the United States as the most influential country, with this role being taken over by Venezuela in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
