Arsenic-resistant microbe could enable new life forms on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a foreign species of bacteria that can live on arsenic, among other things, opens up new possibilities for new life forms on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, it is in their view a sign that life is possible even without the elements previously considered vital.
"This organism has two possibilities."
"He needs to grow either phosphorus or arsenic."
“This makes it something very special, although it’s almost a kind of ‘foreign’ form of life,” Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, who appears on Thursday in the online issue of the journal Science, said in a statement.
So far, six main elements have been considered vital - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
But as the scientists found out, the bacterium in California’s Mono Lake grows even further when it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
“You wonder what else is possible,” said Ariel D. Anbar, a co-author of the Arizona State University report.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists must recognize life and its forms, Anbar said.
The study deals with microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference in which no details of the discovery were announced gave rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report might be about the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that organisms can initiate biochemical processes in other planetary systems using other elements and that the 'standard elements' that we believe are absolutely vital are not necessarily fixed," said Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute at the Open University of Milton Keynes in the United Kingdom.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
"This work is a novelty because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures one element can be replaced by another," Cockell added.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA’s Astrobiological Institute, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because of its high arsenic content.
Since arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, they assumed that microbes exposed to both may be able to replace one element with the other.
"The toxicity of the arsenic is mainly due to the chemical behavior similar to phosphorus."
"This makes it difficult for the organisms to distinguish one element from another."
"However, the difference is so great that arsenic works differently than phosphorus, and it gets into our biochemical system, where it almost smears everything," explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increasing arsenic concentration, adapting and growing.
Although the microbe grows better in phosphorus, it can also survive in arsenic, showing that an arsenic-based life form can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon, on which arsenic is more common.
According to Jamie S. Foster, professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new, but so far there has not been a working example.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth years, she says, so science has assumed that early life forms have used it.
"This gives reason to believe that life may have evolved differently than it did in the early Earth Age," said Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Health Authorities.
