Can politeness connect the separation?
After a campaign of blasphemous words and negativity, little politeness has erupted in Washington this week.
Is it the omen of a real two-party cooperation or a moment of illusion before you quickly return to the struggle of the parties in the capital?
The meeting on Tuesday between President Obama and the tops of Congress did not bring a breakthrough into the big issues that one had to deal with during the so-called "lame duck session", the session at the end of a government period in which no more decisions are made.
After all that you hear, it was neither a polite discussion between two different sides nor a consideration of their shared responsibility to govern, but rather an empty episode of a partial collection of points.
The public meeting of the President’s deficit commission on Wednesday was also civilized, despite the political differences that continue to exist between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months creates mutual respect that obscures the ideological divide that continues to divide members.
This is hardly enough to say that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both sides are now in a test phase - one in which one of the other signs of willingness to cooperate and compromise is called for, while one tries to weigh the limits of public opinion and the patience of the voters after a renewed party war.
Therefore, the meeting on Tuesday itself and its assessment by the participants were limited to a minimum of claims or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and Republicans are too big and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxes, donations, health or expectations, the two sides are miles away from each other.
Last but not least, the November election in Washington voted mildly for at least a short time.
“No question, the tone has changed,” said Pete Wehner, an official representative of the Bush administration, who is now working for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
“This is inevitable after elections.
Elections awaken partisan passions that die again.
And that's good."
On some issues, especially those on the agenda of the “lame duck session,” Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution.”
Bush’s tax cuts will end at the end of the year, and no one will support that.
Both sides want to find a way to get some or all, whether temporarily or permanently.
Similarly, a compromise on increased unemployment benefits is to be expected, if only because Republicans can’t afford to believe the favored tax cuts for the rich, while denying unemployed workers support.
After the meeting on Tuesday at the White House, the optimism has increased that one can agree on these issues during the "lame duck session" and at the same time also ratify the New START contract.
But William Glaston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on urgent issues of the lame duck session "does not necessarily lead to permanent cooperation of the parties when the new 112th Congress is convened in January.
Instead, he says, a phase of non-conformity is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
“After the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation,” he said.
Wehner is also skeptical – and this skepticism is shared by many – that politeness leads to true cooperation.
"I see a lot of what happens from today to 2012 as a pre-fight, or shadow boxing, for the main event of 2012," he said.
The reasons for this have a lot to do with the presentation of the new Republican majority in the White House and with the tea party voters who served their education.
As concerned as the Republican leaders may be that they are playing too high poker, they know that they must try to keep up with their promises to lower government spending and put an end to health reform.
These party lines are already made clear in the initial reactions with regard to the recommendations of the deficit commission, which include tax reform and the raising of some taxes, as well as the raising of retirement age and the lowering of government spending.
Vice-Presidents Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, according to their own opinion, have pushed so much to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that it can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 of the 18 votes within the Commission to make their plan an official recommendation and they are struggling very hard to get even close to that number.
The greatest resistance is found in the elected representatives of the committee, since in financial matters, at least today, there is little room for manoeuvre or little sympathy for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the struggle between the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first fight will take place next year in the form of party clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama regarding the state budget, taxes, and health care system, later followed by a phase of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
The public opinion.
It has been proven that, despite the partisanship of the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
If confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, then both parties must pay careful attention to the public response.
Whoever is condemned to lose will have to change the course and seek compromise.
This may indeed be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are now larger than in the mid-1990s, and they seem to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and Congress Republicans than between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a far broader election in 2012.
In this way, the courtesy shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take a lot more effort on both sides to find a common denominator in the questions that still separate the two.
