At first, no one paid attention to the newcomer, and despite his steeply rising career during the last seasons, at the final spurt last November, everyone put on the victory of Fernando Alonso’s Ferrari.
Without wanting to reduce the skills of German pilot and world champion Sebastian Vettel or the power of Renault’s engine, the “secret weapon” that the Multi Siemens Red Bull put into the hands, and thus created a winning team, has become a legend.
In reality, it is a powerful software for simulating processes that the German company launched in 2007 for purposes that are not related to car racing.
This computer science program, called PLM, was used for the development of assembly chains in factories around the world, power plants and high-precision instruments.
The aim is a faithful reproduction or simulation of a product or process before it is actually built in order to avoid errors and unnecessary costs.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi aircraft and Nissan’s most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens’ industrial department, explains that using this software in the Formula 1 factory Red Bull “in a few hours, almost in real time” can design and execute the changes and improvements that are detected on the races and during the tests.
Russwurm reports that in 1992, on average, ten technicians worked at the racetracks, who were able to introduce a maximum of three or four improvements in a season.
Today, 180 highly qualified young people are employed in Red Bull’s team. With powerful computer systems, they carry out analyses and all sorts of changes to the race car.
The Siemens manager stated that the PLM software is capable of analyzing and improving all components of Red Bull racing cars, except the engine for which Renault is solely responsible.
The materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety elements are changed.
Thanks to advanced production facilities and high-tech autoclaves, the changes can be transferred from the virtual reality of the simulator to reality within less than 24 hours.
The only limit set by this crazy technical perfectionism is the $40 million that a Formula 1 team can spend on their races in a season.
Red Bull has built its high-tech factory for the development and manufacture of its racing cars in a location 50 kilometres from London.
These are two buildings where visits – especially by journalists – are severely restricted.
Everything that happens there is top secret.
The crew includes 580 people, including two pilots, World Champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
But Red Bull's true Formula 1 hero is undoubtedly the newest world champion Sebastian Vetell.
Behind the enormous technological resources that the energy-drink manufacturer places in the services of its participation on the racetracks, there are other protagonists, whose support is invaluable and whose fame is equal to zero.
The head of technology at the plant, Steve Nevey, emphasizes that five years ago it was still possible to say that the progress in R&D for racing cars contributed 50 percent to the victory and the pilots were responsible for the rest.
