In view of the resistance in Europe, three possible ways out of the crisis are beginning to be speculated in Germany.
The first: a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the euro area.
The second: The re-introduction of the German Mark – although that sounds more like science fiction at the moment – is supported by a large part of the public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third: a change in the euro in line with German proposals, which means more macroeconomic control; strict budgetary management; punishment of countries that breach the rules; possibly the suspension of payments of some countries and the expansion of the costs of potential adaptation measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been around for some time, which is why there are no excuses now.
