Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
It says to everyone that, although now unpopular measures must be taken, there will no longer be the old way of functioning of the euro from this date on.
2013 will be the birth year of a new currency area in which the opposing countries will be severely penalized, forced to declare themselves incapacitated and, in this case, the private sector will have to bear some of the costs.
Germany shows us that we need to start a tough growth course, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
The other alternative, which is based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as was pointed out by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
