It is not just about reducing the state deficit to 3% by 2013.
The demands are much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will go into more rest.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities offered to us by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood this as well, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the big companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures from yesterday) points out that despite Merkel’s criticism of creating order in her own house, the hypothesis has been prepared.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn’t look like anything would change about it.
Among the possibilities considered is the fact that we would not have to exclude the euro area, which is filled with little serious countries.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it warned us.
Sports and Rules
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against Ajax show an inventive spirit, but not the will to circumvent a sanction.
The alleged exclusion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League led to a lot of ink being shed about whether it was an unsportsmanlike action or not and whether both players could be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is commonly known, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and as Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will meet the prescribed penalty at the next league match against the Auxerre and thus enter the next stage without cards.
Finally, UEFA’s disciplinary committee punished the club’s coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos—the unwritten but in this sport-observed rules.
Part of the debate that emerged about the case is that a team of Real Madrid football club (who, in his hymn of nobility and honor and on other occasions, had punished his players for similar incidents) played the leading role in this, and the dramatization by Mourinho, who added an episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the statutes, is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether these acts constitute a rule-by-rule circumvention. In fact, this approach adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to circumvent its meaning.
In this case, the damage caused to the sports spirit should be investigated.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not jeopardized by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid the offending players from taking an unjustified advantage from the opposing team, even if that didn’t happen.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we usually understand by cheating or circumvention of rules, because the circumvention of the rule was not done secretly to avoid a sanction, but it should be as conspicuous as possible to punish it by the referee.
The players waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage did the offenders draw from the intentional fouls.
It should be pointed out here that the rival was not put in a more unfavorable position nor were benefits for the played game raised, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club then does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players start the next stage of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it’s a long-term, to a certain degree, unknown advantage, as the team could eventually be eliminated, and with this approach, players receive a penalty and move on to the second card cycle, where they do less than in the first cycle due to card accumulation.
It is not so clear whether this is really an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices are not directed against the sports spirit, which also includes strategic decisions to get the most benefit from the regulations.
In this case, players did not want to circumvent a penalty (that would actually be a clear case of rule circumvention), they preferred to choose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding a penalty or fleeing from it.
Although the boundary between the invention and the regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this matter is a clear case of invention.
I have the impression that polemics arose as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provoked rule transmission.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than aesthetic.
