China maintains its greenhouse gas reduction targets
China’s representative said at COP16 that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and that it would maintain its offer to mine 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gases by 2020.
China holds its offer to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, says Su Wei, the country’s representative at COP16.
At his first public appearance at the 16th United Nations Climate Summit (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country would have made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and shift its industry.
He said his country has invested $245 million over the past four years to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
On the other hand, he stated that China would not change its goals, but would work together with the international community on this matter.
He explained that the Chinese strategy on climate change is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building, and support for pilot programmes.
In all aspects, progress has been made, including the adoption of a new energy law last year, which includes the objectives of reducing the emission of gases, he explained.
On the other hand, he pointed out that in China, the authorities of the states had worked with those of the central state and the municipalities to achieve the goals of energy saving, efficient use of energy and reduction of emissions.
He also stated that some multi-year plans have already been initiated or completed, both those funded by the Chinese government and those that received funds from other countries.
For example, he referred to the effective use of energy programme introduced in the last five years, which had received investment from the United Nations (UNO), the government and private hands.
There is also a provincial-level project on climate change, another to exchange the traditional light bulbs with energy-saving bulbs, and another to mitigate and adapt, he explained.
Martin Krol, scientific government adviser on climate change in this country, confirmed that China’s efforts were far greater than commonly assumed.
He pointed out that the per capita emission of greenhouse gases in China is six tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons. China is responsible for a nine percent overall contribution to environmental pollution.
It is also making unprecedented progress in the field of energy use. The energy efficiency has been increased by twenty per cent in the last five years and by 2020 another is to be done, he explained.
