The U.S. changes the rules for obtaining a visa
Persons must present themselves before their consultation with the consulate at the visa application service points; costs will be reduced in this way.
From 10 January 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa will change at the Embassy of the United States and at the consulates.
In the new procedure, most applicants must present themselves to the Visa Application Service Offices (ASC, the initial letters in English) before their consultation with the consulate.
The personnel of the ASC shall record the biometric data of the applicant, which are checked by the consulate prior to the interview.
The new method has certain advantages for the aspirant, including:
The total cost of processing the visa is reduced, because it is no longer necessary to pay separately the appointment, the processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is handed out.
The applicant shall only make a single payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including temporary workers visas) and $390 for hands and investors.
Those who just want to extend their visa do not have to have a conversation in the consulate, they only have to introduce themselves to the nearest ASC, where they submit their documents and take their fingerprints.
As the biometric data is collected in the ASC, applicants who need a second date for the conversation in the consulate remain there less time than before.
Those applying for the visa in the consulates of Ciudad Ju<0xC3><0xA1>rez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo no longer have to pay the service fee of $26.
Additional information on the new visa application procedure can be found at the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
