Global Plan for the Renewal of Lighting
The UN has proposed a plan in Cancun yesterday to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gas (CFC) equivalent to nearly one-third of the additional reduction that needs to be realized to stabilise the Earth’s climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its place in the steps taken by the UN in Cancun in order to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction commitments by developed countries.
According to the plan submitted yesterday, the main problem would be avoided in the form of 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of the CFC emitted to Earth due to the lighting, if the white-hot bulbs, which so far still constitute a 50 to 70% monopoly on the market, would be replaced by fluorescent or better still, by light-emitting diodes (LEDs).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the emissions of the global fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emissions emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that should downturn global CFC emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt would have to be subtracted from this balance sheet to stabilise the 2 degrees Celsius increase from today to 2020 to prevent it from falling out of control.
In the white-hot bulbs, 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact fluorescent bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced once again by twice.
The compact fluorescent bulbs average between 6000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED light bulbs, such as those introduced by manufacturer Philips this week - by the way, this company has participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white-hot bulb, which provides an indication of the savings potential of the exchange plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that these completely novel light bulbs emit very little heat, they can also work with a regulating resistance.
They do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves, as they contain mercury and that it is therefore necessary to dispose of them as special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless producers provide a point of acceptance.
However, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet, according to the report, is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants that emit significantly more mercury to generate the electricity wasted by the white-hot bulbs.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
The report details the profits that each country would generate thanks to this international programme.
Indonesia would, for example, save one billion dollars a year in the purchase of electricity and eight million tons of CO2, which means an equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power plants whose construction would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
