Climate: how France is appreciating its financial promises
One year after the Copenhagen Treaty, it is time to examine compliance with the rapidly-resolved financing promises (also known as “Fast Start” or early financing) implemented by the developing countries.
And already the rough French fairs have been uncovered.
With the Copenhagen Treaty, developing countries have committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has promised 7.2 billion euros over three years, France 1.26 billion euros (i.e. 420 million per year).
On the occasion of the opening of COP16, the EU has drawn all the registers to convince its partners of their commitment to fast-start financing: detailed progress report of their Member States, press conference, major side events, brochure distribution.
Operation transparency is remarkable and highly valued for its true value: developing countries and civil society like to see it when all developed countries did the same at the same level of precision.
The EU announced that it had released €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on the right track to respect its 7.2 billion commitment in 2012.
But when you look at the details, things are a little more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Treaty, this money should be "new and additional" to ensure that an additional effort has been made without compromising public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what “new and additional” means.
While the EU Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain member states, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the benchmark he considers best.
For example, the European Commission has set itself the benchmark for those in 2009: international funding will be maintained and 150 million will be added over three years as part of the "Fast-Start" funding.
Other countries have chosen similar guidelines, either with regard to the year or with regard to conditions at the level of public development aid.
In return, France felt that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 was "new and additional".
In other words, there are no benchmarks in the expenditure of the previous year or at the global level of public development aid.
In concrete terms, the total amount of French support for developing countries can remain stable (or decrease) - France is proposing to comply with its commitment to "new and additional" financing.
Another crucial element is the breakdown in donations and loans.
There is no rule yet, and everyone chooses their calculation mode.
Some, such as France, find 1 borrowed € as equivalent with 1 donated €.
Obviously, this is difficult to explain: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often linked to emission reduction projects based on the most effective technology) can be justified, it is deceptive to present the euro, which is taken as the equivalent for a donated euro... In addition, only the cost of the loan for the capitalisation country should be counted as the commitment (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing but the following consideration: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by borrowing 91.5% (389.8 million euros) and donating 8.5% (36.1 million euros) - see also the EU document to convince itself of this.
France is the only country in the EU that uses loans to a large extent.
Germany demands 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among other things) are making 100% of their commitments with donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union spends €1 to fulfil its obligations, France only spends 10 cents and understands a similar commitment.
Beautiful Hokuspocus!
All in all, France is operating in its fast-start financing with a double swindle: partly with a further development of the action over time and partly with the reality of financial commitment.
France succeeds in making it believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" million in line with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (since it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitrage) could have a double negative effect; once inside the EU (why do the other member states continue to donate, if it is enough to borrow?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries do not let themselves be completely fooled...
The chapter of early funding is only a small question in a relatively short period of time compared to the totality of discussions about the climate.
But it could be the drop too much in the immense machinery of the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn his lesson from this first year of early funding.
In the first place, France could announce a change in its type of booking for 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of respect for its obligations and equal justice with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, France could bring forward the discussions on the issue of long-term financing (another, crucial and currently discussed topic): one does not escape the question of "predictability" or the type of borrowing of its loans.
France could change its position to be as progressive as it is with other issues.
So the hope is based on the new environment minister Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement about France's fast-start and its vision of "responsibility" as well as the use of loans would naturally raise the international basis of trust necessary for further discussions.
Alarm - Pesticides taken by children
A 10-year-old child takes 81 different chemical substances over the day, according to a study published this Wednesday by the Association of Générations Futures (former movement to protect the rights and respect of coming generations).
The association, which states that its results "do not reflect a statistically significant value given the small number of samples analysed, but represent the illustration character of the problem being treated," had purchased food from a 10-year-old child at meals and a snack at supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September.
These typical meals – including the official recommendations of five fresh fruit and fruit parts, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water a day – were examined, as well as purging laboratories in search of chemical substances, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The plate balance is debilitating: 81 chemical substances, including 42 classified as possibly or probably carcinogenic, and five classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances with endocrine disruptors, according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"Even if the legal limits for each chemical, individually consumed substance are not exceeded in the approximate totality of the cases, it is very well taken from this survey that the reality in which the consumer is exposed to potentially carcinogenic substances or substances with endocrine disrupting factor is alarming," the association notes.
Already at breakfast, the butter and tea with milk alone already contain more than ten of the potentially carcinogenic residues and three proven to be carcinogenic, as well as more than twenty residues that can affect the hormonal system.
The apple imported from Brazil, intended as a snack for the study, has traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to the green beans from Kenya, included in lunch, where the study found traces of an insecticide strictly prohibited in the EU.
In addition, the chop steak, the tuna from the can, even the baguette and gum of pesticides and other chemical substances were spiced.
In tap water, the analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon steak with 34 determined chemical residues was "richest", and even the plastic plate used to warm up the meal in the microwave was not unloaded.
The final risk of this “pollutant cocktail” to the consumer is “probably undervalued,” the study said.
The Alliance Europe Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV) has proposed, for its part, "in view of the urgency of the situation", to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop the "increase in civilizational diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) identified the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
